snippet.textDisplay:
I think Jeremy Johns said it well when he mentioned that Finn’s story was a missed opportunity.
Instead of J.J. Undoing what Rian Johnson did with TLJ they should have rolled with the punches and used it.

Imagine the Resistance beaten down and lacking members to fight back. So what do our heroes do?
Finn determines to go set his fellow stormtroopers free by data mining the families and original names of all his fellow stormtroopers kidnapped as children like himself.
They go on a risky mission to recover this data from some archive. After retrieving it they spread it all over the imperial holonet causing a massive divide in the 1st Order forces.

Thru this impromptu recruitment drive the 1st Order turns on itself and the Resistance rises in ranks overwhelmingly out of nowhere in the eyes of their enemies.

Rey in the meantime is pulled between choosing Kylo or Finn. Kylo legitimately becomes the new villain of the saga, for better or worse, and attempts to secure his new empire, achieving what evil Anakin wanted all the way back in the prequels.
Rey feels him drawing her away from the light promising the same union Darth Vader offered his son in the clouds of Bespin.
She goes to confront him in an attempt to redeem his soul, effectively ending the fight with his transformation back to the light. Only Kylo, not matter how torn he is while feeling the pull back towards the light, he resists in the end fully embracing his fall.
Rey finally chooses Finn as a result, seeing the monster he truly is and engages in a final climactic battle.
She eventually overcomes Kylo and as he’s dying she holds his hand and he affirms he really had affection for her leaving Rey emotionally scarred over his death.

I think this would have been a much better road to travel instead of trying to undue the damage already done.

Just my opinion.

snippet.textDisplay: I highly doubt it's that bad, it's more likely that those that are hating on it overreacted or expected too much of this movie. In my opinion, there was no need for any course correction whatsoever. Rey has never been a "Mary Sue" in any way at all. How does it not flow? It all flowed pretty smoothly to me. I'm guessing a lot of the things people think are dumb or unnecessary actually are smart and make a lot of sense. Why does everyone complain so much about dialogue these days? How does something "feel rushed" or "feel forced" and why are those bad feelings? They should have just revealed Snoke to be Darth Plagueis and put a new spin on that story. Is it really that hard to realize that the emperor could have been ressurected through the force? Far too many fans seem to care way too much about being blown away by the movie instead of being realistic with their expectations and paying attention to the details while looking beyond the surface of what's shown on screen and thinking critically. What's so dumb about choosing to be nobodies? It was probably a choice made to protect themselves. Why is everyone so obsessed with characters having to earn something? How do we know they didn't earn something? Just because it wasn't shown doesn't mean it wasn't earned. It's obvious that Rey took the Skywalker name to honor Luke and Leia, especially Leia who was a maternal figure to her. But I guess most people were too busy making ridiculous complaints to use their brains. Why does everyone have such am issue with Luke choosing to give up the Jedi life to live in isolation as a hermit? BOTH of his former masters, Obi-Wan and Yoda, did the exact same thing and no one had an issue with that. Was Luke not allowed to choose that life? Or arr people just butthurt that he wasn't the hero of the new trilogy? Honestly, I'm so tired of every single thing that comes out causing a divide among fans and I'm pretty sure I'm not alone on that one. If fans would stop being so picky about things that don't need to be nitpicked at all and learn to accept their expectations not being met and not letting that ruin the entire movie for them, and instead keep their brains turned on, use the critical thinking skills we all have, and pay attention to details while using knowledge of the lore and common logic to look between the scenes at what's under the surface of what's shown on screen, these stupid divides would dramatically decrease.

snippet.textDisplay:
FOR STAR WARS FANS
I saw the original SW at the age of 13. Nothing will ever compare to the shock and awe of how amazing the special effects wowed me. I have seen every one of the movies and own them all and don't regret buying any of them. Some are more "ENTERTAINING" then others, but they all were good movies. Note to fans....the only investment you have in the 42 years of the saga is admission, snacks and time. If you think you can write a better saga, go for it, let's see how you do!!! One of the things that drives me mad, is the incessant negitive fodder. Every SW movie after ROTJ has been just ripped from the opening scroll.
#1 it is a "MOVIE"
#2 It is not your vision it is the driectors.
#3 It is HOLLYWOOD get over it!!
#4 George Lucas said, " It's only a movie"
Lastly, just go and don't think about anything. Relax eat popcorn and take it in as it is presented. Then ask yourself, " was I entertained?" I'll bet everyone who is ripping it' was genuinely entertained. The problem is nobody in today's world wants to here positive things, because they don't grab peoples attention like negative press. Thus don't make money.
MAY THE FORCE BE WITH YOU!

snippet.textDisplay: The next to the last chapter of a serialized fiction is no time to decide “you know what...I’m gonna make the movie Iiiii wanna make.  With the results Iiiiii wanna see (Rian Johnson) It’s time to be a team player and set up the team (all the chapters, all storytellers before and after) for the final chapter (for the win).  Here’s the disclaimer again. Please like what you like. If you like the the Last Jedi then great.  If you like Force Awakens, great, but by making these movies connect to Lucas’ movies was to me a huge mistake.  The themes in those movies don’t need updating, they are timeless.  Disney shoulda left 1-6 alone and started their own Star Wars movies (they tried to say any licensed fiction under Lucas were no longer valid anyways. “Legends”) but regardless, here we are.  Enjoy what I can and move on is all I can do after 40+ years.

snippet.textDisplay: After watching Ep 8 I had literally no motivation whatsoever to see what happened next in Star Wars Land. I could not have cared less. snippet.textDisplay: I really enjoyed it, and not really because of the fan service. for me, I thought it worked in the larger universe ... fuck the new characters, you don't need buy-in for them  -  I thought it was clever that they used them as the expanded vessels they were to get the expanded story out there and fairly tied up. I think you're all armchair cowboys who just love looking for things to snipe at. Try being constructive ... being overly critical has become the standard now for star wars. And that's a pity. Heaps of awesome stuff in this, including the very fast pacing which is totally consistent with the original series.
